reviews.review_text: great aud Thank you Mr. Brennekke and friends for these uploads. I think I was in front of this operation on the last night of the tour and I hope I didn’t give you my cold.  I never liked the soundboards from this year.  So crowded with Bruce, strangely “crunchy” and hard on the ears for long periods in headphones has always been my experience with ’91 soundboards.  At the time, I longed for the soundboards in order to hear the nuances, but nowadays, I think these shows are better experienced via great auds like this series of uploads.  They sounded great in the venues that year and this recording is representative: full and fat and in the moment.  I can appreciate the short Playin’ and Dark Star jams really for the first time in the first two nights because these recordings provide the space for them to exist, not all smushed up against the speaker grills by the pounding piano like on the soundboards.  While the set starts unpromisingly with Picasso Moon, it is quickly revealed to be one in which they feel like taking their time getting to wherever they’re going.  A mid-set TLEO tells you that much and so by the time we’re at the jam in Music Never Stopped, the set seems longer that it probably is. I wouldn’t know.  I forgot about the time way way back.  Anyway, it’s a nice Aiko for the period, LLR doesn’t disappoint and is over the top as usual and the rest of the pre-drums really is a nice set of curveballs.  New Speedway from the 1991 perspective: quaint.  How many miles indeed?
